<paragraph blockId="73.[151,736,1910,1936]" box="[151,736,1910,1936]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,736,1910,1936]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,736,1910,1936]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
Putative 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[262,441,1910,1936]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="charithonia">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[262,441,1910,1936]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">H. charithonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
x 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Felder &amp; R. Felder" authorityYear="1859" box="[471,643,1910,1936]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruvianus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[471,643,1910,1936]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">H. peruvianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hybrid
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="73.[151,1436,1974,2035]" lastBlockId="74.[151,1436,151,464]" lastPageId="74" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
Hybrid #159 (not illustrated in Mallet 
<emphasis box="[587,644,1974,1998]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">et al.</emphasis>
(2007). Ecuador: Pichincha, Río Toachi, 
<quantity box="[1116,1198,1975,1999]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" unit="m" value="1700.0">1700m</quantity>
. 1996 leg. C. Jiggins (Jiggins collection). This butterfly, documented by 
<bibRefCitation box="[729,1008,2010,2035]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" refId="ref15902" refString="Mallet, J., McMillan, W. O. &amp; Jiggins, C. D. (1998) Mimicry and warning color at the boundary between races and subspecies. In: Howard, D. J. &amp; Berlocher, S. H. (Eds.), Endless forms. Oxford University Press, Oxford, pp. 390 - 403." type="book chapter">Jiggins &amp; Davies (1998)</bibRefCitation>
, has an 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[1100,1266,2010,2034]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="charithonia">
<emphasis box="[1100,1266,2010,2034]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">H. charithonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
phenotype (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[151,247,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 169" captionStartId="73.[151,255,1057,1080]" captionTargetBox="[230,1354,735,1021]" captionTargetId="figure@73.[217,1369,721,1035]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURE 169. H. charithonia vasquezae Comstock &amp; Brown, 1950 (dorsal, ventral). Guatemala: Monte Rico, Santa Rosa. (image source: https://cliniquevetodax.com/Heliconius/pages/charithonia%20vazquezae.html)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1459478/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Fig. 169</figureCitation>
), but a distribution of allozyme alleles that suggested to them an F1 hybrid between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[1190,1355,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="charithonia">
<emphasis box="[1190,1355,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">H. charithonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Felder &amp; R. Felder" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruvianus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">H. peruvianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[298,402,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 171" captionStartId="74.[151,255,897,920]" captionTargetBox="[525,1063,544,865]" captionTargetId="figure@74.[505,1081,515,876]" captionTargetPageId="74" captionText="FIGURE 171. H. peruvianus C. Felder &amp; R. Felder, 1859 (dorsal). Ecuador: &quot;Esmeraldas, Lita, Chuchuví&quot; (locality data erroneous—K. Willmott pers. comm.). (image source: https://cliniquevetodax.com/Heliconius/pages/peruvianus.html). This taxon, elevated from subspecific status by Jiggins &amp; Davies (1998), is a dry-forest segregate from western Ecuador like H. himera." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1459482/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Fig. 171</figureCitation>
). Mallet 
<emphasis box="[517,580,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">et al.</emphasis>
(2007) interpreted it as backcross to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[1047,1220,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="charithonia">
<emphasis box="[1047,1220,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">H. charithonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, likely due to its homozygous condition of malic enzyme for an allele that is nearly absent from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Felder &amp; R. Felder" authorityYear="1859" box="[1052,1211,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruvianus">
<emphasis box="[1052,1211,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">H. peruvianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. There are no fixed differences among the alleles examined by 
<bibRefCitation box="[632,905,260,285]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" refId="ref15902" refString="Mallet, J., McMillan, W. O. &amp; Jiggins, C. D. (1998) Mimicry and warning color at the boundary between races and subspecies. In: Howard, D. J. &amp; Berlocher, S. H. (Eds.), Endless forms. Oxford University Press, Oxford, pp. 390 - 403." type="book chapter">Jiggins &amp; Davies (1998)</bibRefCitation>
between these two species, so it is possible that it is 
<emphasis box="[202,376,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[202,372,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="charithonia">H. charithonia</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
(Also note that prior to Jiggins and Davies' study, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. Felder &amp; R. Felder" authorityYear="1859" box="[958,1119,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peruvianus">
<emphasis box="[958,1119,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">H. peruvianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was viewed as a race of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Heliconius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="charithonia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">H. charithonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
